ba1382ef-1e3e-49e0-9586-ca3a7d5ce949.0e7c5cb9-fdea-4eb6-83af-015d53f119c3.prompt=vCenter Host\: ba1382ef-1e3e-49e0-9586-ca3a7d5ce949.120e5dc8-42b7-42fc-bb3b-645399349d6f.description=
This operation waits for the number of seconds specified in the "seconds" input.

Inputs\:
    seconds - The number of seconds to wait.

Results\:
    resultString – This is the primary output. It contains the "completed sleep" message if the operation completed successfully and an error message otherwise. 

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.
ba1382ef-1e3e-49e0-9586-ca3a7d5ce949.1fb39910-8130-4526-b561-feb8cb2b8196.description=
This operation iterates through a list of values. It is not recommended to modify the value of the "list" and "separator" inputs during the iteration process.

Inputs\:
    list - The list to iterate through.
    separator - A delimiter separating the list elements.
Default value\: ‘,’ (comma) 

Results\:
    resultString - The current list element (if the response is "has more").

Responses\:
    has more - Another value was found in the list and it has been returned.
    no more - The iterator has gone through the entire list. This response is returned once per list iteration.  A subsequent call to the List iterator operation restarts the list iteration process.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Note\:
   The position of the iterator in the list is tracked by each step's unique identifier. Therefore, you can simultaneously iterate through the same list from multiple steps.
ba1382ef-1e3e-49e0-9586-ca3a7d5ce949.4437235a-5fdf-4692-9274-0e47e7dd24d4.description=This flow reverts a virtual machine to an existing named snapshot. Inputs\: vCenterHost - VMware host hostname or IP. vCenterUsername - VMware username. vCenterPassword - VMware user's password. vCenterPort - Port to connect on. vCenterProtocol - Connection protocol. Valid values\: "https", "http" closeSession - Close the internally kept VMware Infrastructure API session at completion of operation. Valid values\: "true", "false" virtualMachine - Primary Virtual Machine identifier. Inventorypath (Datacenter/vm/Folder/MyVM), Name of VM, IP (IPv4 or IPv6 depending upon ESX version), hostname (full), UUID, or the VM id (vm-123,123). vmIdentifierType - Virtual machine identifier type (inventorypath, name, ip, hostname, uuid, vmid). snapshotName - Name of snapshot. vmDatacenter - Virtual machine's datacenter. If host is ESX(i) use "ha-datacenter". shouldPowerOn - Specify if the flow should power on the virtual machine after reverting to snapshot. Valid values\: "true", "false" Default\: "false" Responses\: success - The flow completed successfully. failure - Something went wrong. Returns\: returnResult - The flow primary result containing a success message in case of success or the reason of failure in case of failure. snapshots - The current snapshot tree for the given virtual machine. Notes\: 1) Inventory Path Formatting\: If host is an ESX server inventory path will be\: ha-datacenter/vm/ . If host is a vCenter the inventory path will be\: /vm// . The / part of the path is based on the "Virtual Machines & Templates" view in the vCenter client. The inventory path is case sensitive. ba1382ef-1e3e-49e0-9586-ca3a7d5ce949.4fe1b2aa-dc24-458e-9fa0-d870729e0365.prompt=vCenter Password\: ba1382ef-1e3e-49e0-9586-ca3a7d5ce949.691e4a0a-3204-4208-b677-ef1672c99110.description=
This operation does not do anything. It can be used to filter flow variables by defining them as inputs and filtering them in the Results tab.

Inputs\:
    field1 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field2 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field3 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field4 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the value of  "field1" as it was specified at input or when filtered. 

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
ba1382ef-1e3e-49e0-9586-ca3a7d5ce949.8efebfb5-26e0-4096-8caa-cf70bf30763c.prompt=vCenter Username\: ba1382ef-1e3e-49e0-9586-ca3a7d5ce949.a6f1896c-87c0-4552-84d4-aafc61ef33c2.description=This flow starts a virtual machine (power on) and eventually waits for the guest operating system based on "waitGuest" input. Inputs\: vCenterHost - VMware host hostname or IP. vCenterUsername - VMware username. vCenterPassword - VMware user's password. vCenterPort - Port to connect on. Example\: 80, 443 Default\: 443 vCenterProtocol - Connection protocol. Valid values\: http, https Default\: 443 closeSession - Close the internally kept VMWare Infrastructure API session at completion of operation. Valid values\: true, false. virtualMachine - Primary Virtual Machine identifier. Inventory path (Datacenter/vm/Folder/MyVM), Name of VM, IP (IPv4 or IPv6 depending upon ESX version), hostname (full), UUID, or the VM id (vm-123,123). vmIdentifierType - Virtual machine identifier type Valid values\: inventorypath, name, ip, hostname, uuid, vmid. vmDatacenter - Virtual machine's datacenter. If host is ESX(i) use "ha-datacenter". waitGuest - If "true" the flow will wait for the virtual machine's guest operating system, otherwise it will just start the virtual machine. Default\: true poolingRetries - The number of checks the flow will do to the guest operating system to check if it's in the expected state. Default\: 10 poolingInterval - The seconds the flow will wait between two checks of the guest operating state. Default\: 10 Responses\: success - The flow completed successfully. failure - Something went wrong. Returns\: returnResult - The flow primary result containing a success message in case of success or the reason of failure in case of failure. Notes\: 1) Inventory Path Formatting\: If host is an ESX server, inventory path will be\: ha-datacenter/vm/ . If host is a vCenter, the inventory path will be\: /vm//. The / part of the path is based on the "Virtual Machines & Templates" view in the vCenter client.
